    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-08-08T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-08-08T03:00:00-05:00" n="206"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d206">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12095: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-08-08T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 8, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 8—6:24 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>914. Following from American Consul General at Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“August 7, noon. My August 7, 11 a.m. <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_LW1">Lo Wen-kan</persName> told me over the
                            telephone that <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WC1">Wang</persName>
                            <note n="19" xml:id="d206fn19">
                                <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WC1">Wang Ching-wei</persName>,
                                President of the Executive Yuan (Premier). His resignation was
                                rejected on August 22, 1932, but Vice President <persName
                                    corresp="frus1932v03#p_STV1">T. V. Soong</persName> was selected
                                to be Acting President of the Executive Yuan.</note> had resigned
                            because Marshal <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CT2">Chang</persName>
                            would not resist Japanese invasion and that he, Lo, entirely sided with
                                <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WC1">Wang</persName>. He referred
                            me to published telegrams of <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WC1"
                                >Wang</persName> for full explanation of the present controversy. In
                            recent conversation with me <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_LW1"
                                >Lo</persName> bitterly criticized <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_CK3">Chiang Kai-shek</persName>. Appearances
                            are that the present Government will be disrupted over the question of
                            ‘resistance or non-resistance’.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
